An '''electron–ion collider (EIC)''' is a proposed<ref name="EICwhitepaper">[https://arxiv.org/abs/1212.1701 A. Accardi et al., “Electron Ion Collider: The Next QCD Frontier - Understanding the glue that binds us all,”] 2012.</ref> type of [[particle accelerator]] designed to collide [[Spin polarization|spin-polarized]] beams of [[electrons]] and [[ions]], in order to study the properties of nuclear matter in detail via [[deep inelastic scattering]]. In 2015, the [[Department of Energy]] Nuclear Science Advisory Committee (NSAC) named the construction of an electron–ion collider one of the top priorities for the near future in [[nuclear physics]] in the United States.<ref>https://science.energy.gov/~/media/np/nsac/pdf/2015LRP/2015_LRPNS_091815.pdf</ref>
== Proposed designs== Both [[Brookhaven National Laboratory]] and [[Thomas Jefferson National Accelerator Facility]] have proposed designs for an EIC.
=== eRHIC === Brookhaven National Laboratory's conceptual design, eRHIC, proposes upgrading the existing [[Relativistic Heavy Ion Collider]], which collides beams light to heavy ions including polarized protons, with a polarized electron facility.<ref>[https://arxiv.org/abs/1409.1633 E. C. Aschenauer et al., “eRHIC Design Study: An Electron-Ion Collider at BNL,”] 2014.</ref>
=== JLEIC === Jefferson Lab's conceptual design, JLEIC (formerly known as MEIC),<ref>[https://arxiv.org/abs/1504.07961 S. Abeyratne et al., “MEIC Design Summary,”] 2015. </ref> proposes upgrading the existing [[Thomas_Jefferson_National_Accelerator_Facility#Accelerator|CEBAF]] 12 GeV electron accelerator with an electron ring built from magnets previously used in the [[SLAC_National_Accelerator_Laboratory#PEP-II|PEP-II accelerator]], and an ion complex built from new magnets.
